opendcl-host-pickers â€” entity / layer / block pickers via HAL
=============================================================

See also: opendcl.plan, opendcl-wire-protocol.issue,
opendcl-runtime-core.issue, opendcl-controls.issue.

Context
-------

Several OpenDCL controls and dialogs prompt the user to *pick*
something from the host CAD drawing â€” an entity, a layer, a block
reference, a colour, a linetype, a point on screen. Real OpenDCL
delegates straight to AutoCAD's `ssget` / `entsel` / colour dialog
etc. In clautolisp the host is the HAL: `MockHost` today,
`AutocadHost` / `BricscadHost` etc. tomorrow.

This means a picker control is a *reverse synchronous* call:

  GUI     â†’ runtime :  (:pick-request 42 :entity (:filter "*LINE"))
  runtime â†’ HAL     :  prompt user via the active host backend
  runtime â†’ GUI     :  (:pick-reply 42 (:ok ((:type :entity)
                                              (:handle "abc")
                                              (:layer "0"))))

Same request/reply envelope as property get/set; just initiated
from the GUI side. The HAL gets a new `request-pick KIND OPTIONS`
entry point that each backend implements.

In scope
--------

  1. HAL surface. Add to `clautolisp/autolisp-host/source/api.lisp`:

         (defgeneric request-pick (host kind options)
           (:documentation "Prompt the user for KIND (:entity,
              :layer, :block, :color, :linetype, :point, â€¦).
              OPTIONS is a plist. Returns either
                (:ok <picked-value>)
              or
                (:cancel)
              or
                (:error CODE MESSAGE)."))

     MockHost answers from a scripted queue (mirrors the existing
     `mock-host-prompt-stream` pattern). Real-host backends will
     wrap `ssget` / `entsel` / the colour dialog when those land.

  2. Wire dispatch. The runtime, on receiving `(:pick-request RID
     KIND OPTIONS)`, calls the active host's `request-pick`,
     translates the result into a reply, and writes
     `(:pick-reply RID â€¦)` back. Keep this in the wire bridge,
     not in the builtins â€” it must work for *every* picker
     control without per-control glue.

  3. Picker controls. The first wave:
       - EntityPicker        â†’ `(:pick-request RID :entity â€¦)`
       - LayerPicker         â†’ `(:pick-request RID :layer â€¦)`
       - BlockPicker         â†’ `(:pick-request RID :block â€¦)`
       - ColorPicker         â†’ `(:pick-request RID :color â€¦)`
       - LinetypePicker      â†’ `(:pick-request RID :linetype â€¦)`

     Each renders as a small composite â€” text-display plus an
     ellipsis button; the button fires the pick request and the
     reply populates the text field. The Qt control catalogue is
     extended in `opendcl-controls.issue`.

  4. AutoLISP-visible result shape. Picked values use the same
     tagged-plist shape AutoLISP code already sees from
     `entsel` / `tblsearch`:
         (:entity (:handle "abc") (:layer "0") (:type :line))
     so user dcl_* event handlers can consume them without
     translation.

  5. MockHost scripted scenarios. Conformance corpus fixtures
     under `opendcl-conformance.issue` script the host with a
     queue of canned picks; tests assert the round-trip.

Out of scope
------------

  - Real-host backends (`AutocadHost`, `BricscadHost`). They land
    when the broader HAL-to-CAD bridge does, and will simply
    implement `request-pick` on their side.
  - Interactive geometry (drag-pick, snap modes). V1 picks return a
    single result; rubber-banding waits for V2.

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - `request-pick` defined on `host` and implemented by MockHost;
    its `:cancel` and `:error` paths covered by tests.
  - At least three of the picker controls work end-to-end under
    MockHost with scripted answers.
  - autolisp-spec gains a "Host Pickers" subsection enumerating
    `KIND` values, options accepted, and result shape.

Notes
-----

This is where clautolisp's headless model pays off: the picker can
be scripted from a test fixture, so a full dialog flow that ends
"â€¦ click EntityPicker, the user picks line 'abc'" is reproducible
in CI without a CAD host. Build that ergonomic harness as part of
this ticket.
